TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ríos-Rull, José-Víctor
T1  - Life-Cycle Economies and Aggregate Fluctuations
PY  - 1996
Y1  - 1996/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297891
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
SP  - 465
EP  - 489
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Do the implications for business cycle issues change when we switch from studying infinitely-lived, representative-agent models to more sophisticated demographic structures with finitely lived agents? This article addresses that question by using a large, overlapping-generations model that is calibrated to U.S. demographic properties, microeconomic evidence, and National Income and Product Accounts. The finding is that the answers obtained are basically the same for the two kinds of models. The article also explores the relative volatility of hours across age groups, an issue that cannot be addressed by using the infinitely-lived, representative-agent abstraction.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297891
ER  - 



